            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How to use the meeting calculator</h2>
              <h3>1. Find a fair time across time zones</h3>
              <p>
                In the <strong>Time zone helper</strong> tab, choose the meeting
                date, base time, and the organizer’s time zone. Add participants
                and select their time zones. The table shows each person’s local
                time and whether it falls inside typical working hours
                (09:00–17:00).
              </p>
              <p>
                Use the <strong>Suggest earlier</strong> and
                <strong>Suggest later</strong> buttons to nudge the meeting time
                until most participants are in green (within working hours)
                instead of red (outside hours).
              </p>

              <h3>2. Set up duration and participant costs</h3>
              <p>
                Switch to <strong>Meeting setup</strong> to define the duration,
                working hours per year, and currency. For each participant you
                can choose:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Annual salary</strong> – converted to hourly using
                  working hours per year.
                </li>
                <li><strong>Hourly rate</strong> – used directly.</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Day rate</strong> – divided by 8 hours by default.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Click <strong>Copy names from time zone tab</strong> to avoid
                retyping participants. You can still edit or remove people
                independently in each tab.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Estimate and track meeting cost in real time</h3>
              <p>
                In the <strong>Cost &amp; live ticker</strong> tab, the
                calculator shows:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Estimated cost</strong> for the full planned duration.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Live cost</strong> that increases while the meeting is
                  running.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Average cost per person</strong> for the planned
                  duration.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Press <strong>Start live meeting</strong> when the meeting
                begins. You can pause and resume the ticker, or reset it if the
                meeting is cancelled or restarted.
              </p>

              <h2>Formulas used by the meeting cost calculator</h2>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>1. Hourly cost from annual salary</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Hourly cost} = \dfrac{\text{Annual
                  salary}}{\text{Working hours per year}}\)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  <strong>2. Hourly cost from day rate</strong>
                </p>
                <p>\(\text{Hourly cost} = \dfrac{\text{Day rate}}{8}\)</p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  <strong>3. Cost per participant for a meeting</strong>
                </p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Participant cost} = \text{Hourly cost} \times
                  \dfrac{\text{Duration (minutes)}}{60}\)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2"><strong>4. Total meeting cost</strong></p>
                <p>\(\text{Total cost} = \sum \text{Participant cost}\)</p>
                <p class="mt-2"><strong>5. Live cost ticker</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Live cost}(t) = \sum \left(\text{Hourly cost}_i \times
                  \dfrac{t}{3600}\right)\)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-1 text-xs text-gray-500">
                  where \(t\) is the elapsed time in seconds.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Tips for running better, cheaper meetings</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Invite only decision-makers and contributors.</strong>
                  Observers can often get a written summary instead.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Shorten default durations.</strong> Try 15–25 minutes
                  instead of 60 where possible.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Batch status updates.</strong> Replace recurring
                  status meetings with async updates plus a shorter Q&amp;A.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Use the cost as a sanity check.</strong> If the cost
                  looks high for the decision at stake, adjust scope, attendees,
                  or format.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

